});

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Do you have a showroom in Toronto?",
    a: "No. Lux Jewels operates entirely online. Consultations are 30-40 minute video calls via Zoom or Google Meet. Rings are delivered via FedEx Priority, fully insured, with signature required. I've operated this way since 2007 — not because I can't open a showroom, but because an online process is faster, less expensive for clients, and genuinely works better for a custom product."
  },
  {
    q: "Why should I buy from an online jeweller instead of a Toronto showroom?",
    a: "The honest answer is lower overhead equals lower prices for equivalent quality. Toronto showroom rent, sales staff, and display inventory are real costs that get embedded into ring prices. An online specialist has lower overhead and passes that back. You also get direct access to me — not a sales rep working toward a commission — and access to stone inventory from multiple suppliers rather than whatever a single showroom happens to carry."
  },
  {
    q: "How does the consultation work if I'm in Toronto?",
    a: "You book a 30-40 minute video call via Zoom or Google Meet. We discuss your style preferences, stone priorities (shape, size, colour, clarity), setting preferences, and budget. After the call, I identify candidate stones and follow up with pricing and photos. If you'd like to proceed, I present CAD designs before production begins. Everything is async-friendly — you don't have to be available outside work hours."
  },
  {
    q: "How does delivery work in Toronto?",
    a: "All rings ship via FedEx Priority, fully insured, with signature required. Typical delivery to Toronto addresses is next-day from ship date. You'll receive tracking information when the order ships. If no one is available to sign on the first attempt, FedEx will schedule a reattempt or hold at a local FedEx location for pickup."
  },
  {
    q: "What lab-grown engagement rings do you carry for Toronto clients?",
    a: "Every shape in our collection is available — oval, emerald cut, round brilliant, pear, cushion, solitaire, halo, three-stone, radiant, vintage-inspired. All stones are IGI-certified. Custom design is available from a free consultation. We don't carry a display-case inventory — every ring is made to order for the specific client, with the specific stone grade, metal, and setting they've chosen."
  },
  {
    q: "Are your lab-grown diamonds IGI certified?",
    a: "Yes. Every lab-grown diamond we work with comes with an IGI grading certificate and a laser girdle inscription. The inscription matches the certificate number, so you can verify the stone you received matches the certification you paid for. If a seller can't give you a specific IGI or GIA certificate number for the stone before you purchase it, that's a problem."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between you and other Toronto lab-grown jewellers?",
    a: "The most significant difference is my track record. I founded Lux Jewels in 2007 and became the first Canadian jeweller to specialize exclusively in lab-grown stones in 2015. That's over a decade ahead of the national chains adding lab-grown to their display cases. It's also a different service model — you're working directly with the founder and designer, not a salesperson, and the entire process is built around your specific preferences rather than an existing inventory."
  },
  {
    q: "Can I get a ring for under C$2,000 in Toronto?",
    a: "Yes, depending on your specifications. A 0.5-0.75ct oval or round lab-grown diamond in a simple 14K solitaire setting can fall under C$2,000. The variables that push price up are carat weight, clarity grade, colour grade, and setting complexity. <a href='https://luxjewels.com/booking-appointment/' target='_blank' rel='noopener'>Book a free consultation</a> and we'll find the best stone for your specific budget."
  },
];
---

<Base title={title} description={description} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
